07979nam a2200937Ia 9781447300373DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20132013xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97814473003737 a10.51952/97814473003732doi  a(DE-B1597)646569  a(OCoLC)859389603  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcGB-BST 4aHV6025b.V35 2013 7aSOC0040002bisacsh04a36422300aValues in Criminology and Community Justice /ced. by Malcolm Cowburn, Marian Duggan, Anne Robinson, Paul Senior. 1aBristol : bPolicy Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (384 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tA brief introduction -- tNotes on contributors -- tValues of criminological theories -- tJudging offenders: the moral implications of criminological theories -- tPostmodernism and criminological thought: ‘Whose science? Whose knowledge?’ -- tMarxist criminology: whose side, which values? -- tA contemporary reflection on feminist criminology: whose side are we on? -- tBringing the boys back home: re-engendering criminology -- tNew ‘racisms’ and prejudices? The criminalisation of ‘Asian’ -- tThe value(s) of cultural criminology -- tJustifying ‘green’ criminology: values and ‘taking sides’ in an ecologically informed social science -- tValues in criminal justice -- tA moral in the story? Virtues, values and desistance from crime -- tThe value of values in probation practice? -- tDevelopments in police education in England and Wales: values, culture and ‘common-sense’ policing -- tRace, religion and human rights: valuable lessons from prison -- tThe public–private divide: which side is criminal justice on? -- tWorking with victims: values and validations -- tMoney as the measure of man: values and value in the politics of reparation -- tValues in research, policy and practice -- tThe Emperor’s new clothes: can Big Society deliver criminal justice? -- tWhat’s valuable, what’s valued in today’s youth justice? -- tEconomic values and evidence: evaluating criminal justice policy -- tReflections on values and ethics in narrative inquiry with (ex-)offenders -- tWorking with different values: extremism, hate and sex crimes -- tValue for money? The politics of contract research -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe way we think about crime and the way that society responds to it are imbued with values that can determine what is considered important and what gets attention. Sometimes values that are claimed may not be the values expressed in practice, as we see in the multiple and confusing discourses about victims and offenders, punishment and protection, rights and responsibilities. This collection of writings considers values in crime theory, criminal justice and research practice, uncovering the many different 'sides' – to echo Howard Becker's famous phrase – that criminologists, policy makers and researchers take. It spans Marxist, postmodernist and feminist perspectives on criminology, analyses of the dynamics of race, gender and age, research methods and ethics, the working of the criminal justice system and engages with current debates about new challenges for criminology, such as the green movement and Islamophobia. This is a timely and thought-provoking collection which will be of interest to academics and students in criminology and criminal justice, and on professional courses, such as probation and youth justice practice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aCrimexGovernment policyzGreat Britain. 0aCriminal justice, Administration ofxGovernment policyzGreat Britain. 0aCriminologyxPhilosophy. 0aCriminology. 0aPolicezGreat Britain. 0aRestorative justice. 0aValues. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Cr